This porting note should be updated, as you've now made it a reducible definition: clearly it hasn't broken anything but I think we shouldn't leave this in in the current form.
I copy+pasted it. Is there any difference between an `abbrev` and a `@[reducible] def` in Lean 4?
Oh, grand. I am a little unclear on the differences between these things.

There is at least a minor [difference](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/270676-lean4/topic/changing.20reducibility.20for.20type.20class.20inference/near/411940454): you can't write `abbrev` on a recursive definition.

Further `abbrev` [adds](https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/blob/b0fe9d6cdca82723134d61f8fe23a8c674f308b7/src/Lean/Elab/DefView.lean#L47-L53) `@[inline]`.
I think it's fine to leave the comment, as it's orthogonal to this moving-things-around PR, but it would also be fine to update the comment replacing `abbrev` everywhere with "reducible def".

Just checking: is this a weaker set of imports than `Mathlib.Data.Set.Basic` originally had. If so, great!

If not (i.e. you've had to add imports from some later file than `Mathlib.Data.Set.Basic` in order to move definitions from that file to here), then I'd like to know exactly what was added.
No, those ones are no problem at all. Please proceed!
